In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 prisoners escaped from prison in the Indonesian province of Central Sulawesi.
Escape became possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when the prisoners in the prison of the city of Palu demanded their release in connection with the tremors.
More than 330 prisoners rioted and set fire to the institution.
The police officers who arrived at the scene partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself was seriously damaged, and the guards have difficulty holding prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi has increased to 832 people.
In this regard, it has not yet been possible to establish transport links, electricity and communication with some areas of the island.
