The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73-th session of the UN General Assembly to be successful for Russia and does not exclude that it will be able to become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global problems.
“The uniqueness of the current 73-th session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric, to which we are almost accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia, was now an order of magnitude more muted,” the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by Rossiyskaya Gazeta.
He explained that in previous years, Russia was sometimes “marked as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with Ebola, along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this series, in any case, in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which in this regard was expressed unanimously.”
At the 73-th session, Kosachev stressed, "Russia's topic in a negative way was practically absent."
“If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of foreign Affairs of Germany, I now do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was absolutely not exactly,” the politician said, noting that Russia “was no longer a certain wall that is being trained by the strikes with a tennis ball.”
The head of the profile committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates a trend that, in his opinion, “will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, in two, three.”
“I do not rule out that the current session in a sense can be a turning point,” Kosachev admitted, explaining that “too many examples of how Russia manages to move forward in international affairs with the connection.”
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
“Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time,” the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact that he believes that there is an “adequate, sound perception of Russia as not just possible – an integral participant in solving global problems of our time.”
“I don’t want to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that we are going through a point somewhere beyond where the movement will no longer be reversed, it will be moving forward,” he added.
Another “interesting and important feeling” in this context, Kosachev called “a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop.”
“I was at a lot of meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different,” the chairman of the Soviet Federation committee said.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that “the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas about how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problems of migration.”
