The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” breaks another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
Apparently, the people of Germany began to seriously become tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country became a coveted goal for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The most obvious are the recent opinion polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party “Alternative for Germany” is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to the second line in the ranking of folk sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap in one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is impossible not to note the fact that the AfD created in 2013 from a small group of Eurosceptic economists has managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings continues to hold the ruling block of the CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, support for the Angela Merkel bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, which heads the German government for a fourth consecutive term, is also decreasing.
Today, 48 percent of Germans are in support of Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
We add that the social democrats are “green” (15%), the left (11%) and the liberals (10%).
Evolution of "Alternative"
The Alternative for Germany party was established in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included immigrants from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially stood in opposition to the government, but at first dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed the “sponsorship” of the weak EU economies by Germany, did not rule out the possibility of returning to the German mark and the full withdrawal of the country from the European Union.
Amid deepening the immigration crisis, the AfD political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party that occupied the niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, having received 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the Alternative for Germany will have seats in the European Parliament.
